<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Lou Frey Institute Speakers Call for More Energy-Efficient Homes, Less Reliance on Fossil Fuels</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Chad Binette
		
		<span class="date">April 3, 2007</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE711/en_US/freycrop.jpg" height="" width=""  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: Jacque Brund</p>
			
			<p>Jim Fenton of UCF's Florida Solar Energy Center gave an economic perspective on the benefits of energy-efficient appliances, fluorescent light bulbs and solar power.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004102c4c1d99011146fc1c320075c0">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
							
								<h3>Story Images</h3>
								<ul id="story_images">
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004102c4c1d99011146fc1c320075c0&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=0">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE711/en_US/leefull.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004102c4c1d99011146fc1c320075c0&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=1">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE711/en_US/loufull.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
					
						
						
							
						<li>
						<a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004102c4c1d99011146fc1c320075c0&amp;img_mode=1&amp;index=2">
							<img width="100" alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE711/en_US/fentonfull.jpg"  />
						</a>
						</li>
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			</ul><p  class="note">Click thumbnails for full-size images.</p>
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:ddobson@mail.ucf.edu">Doug Dobson, Lou Frey Institute</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-4018</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:cbinette@mail.ucf.edu">Chad Binette, News & Information</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-6312</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.loufrey.org">Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p><state /><place />Florida</place /></state /> residents, whose homes are the least energy-efficient in the nation, would become better stewards of the environment and economy if they switched to energy-efficient appliances, fluorescent light bulbs and solar power, the director of the <place /><placename />Florida</placename /> <placename />Solar</placename /> <placename />Energy</placename /> <placetype />Center</placetype /></place /> at the <place /><placetype />University</placetype /> of <placename />Central Florida</placename /></place /> said Monday.</p><p>Jim Fenton was one of more than a dozen UCF faculty members, environmental experts and political leaders who spoke during Environmental Policy: Issues, Concerns and Solutions, a daylong Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government symposium. Sociology professor Penelope Canan, a former executive director of the Global Carbon Project, and Martin Wanielista, director of the <place /><placename />UCF</placename /> <placename />Stormwater</placename /> <placename />Management</placename /> <placetype />Academy</placetype /></place />, also addressed the crowd in the Student Union.</p><p>About 350 students from nine high and middle schools around the region attended the symposium, and many others in the state and nation watched portions of the event on a live Internet broadcast.</p><p>While several panelists explained the environmental importance of issues such as global warming, air quality and water quality, Fenton added an economic perspective.</p><p>We ship $20 billion a year outside <state /><place />Florida</place /></state /> to purchase fossil fuels, Fenton said. </p><p>Homes generate more than half of the states energy use, so residents can make a big difference by taking steps such as buying Energy Star-certified windows, refrigerators and dishwashers and installing fluorescent lights, Fenton said. He added that using Gossamer ceiling fans, which were invented at the <place /><placename />Florida</placename /> <placename />Solar</placename /> <placename />Energy</placename /> <placetype />Center</placetype /></place />, can help to save energy. More than 1 million of the fans developed by research scientist Danny Parker have been sold. </p><p>Photovoltaic cells that harness energy from the sun can improve energy savings even more, Fenton said, noting that the cost of solar energy will fall below the cost of other sources such as coal and nuclear.</p><p>Its cheaper, Fenton said. Thats the nice thing about sunshine.</p><p>The evening keynote addresses on The Future of Floridas Environment were given by former U.S. Sen. and Florida Gov. Bob Graham; Nat Reed, a former assistant secretary of the U.S. Department of the Interior; and Jake Varn, a development lawyer in Tallahassee. </p><p>Ana Unruh Cohen, a senior policy advisor with the Select Committee for Energy Independence and Global Warming, and Manik Nikki Roy, director of congressional affairs for the <place /><placename />Pew</placename /> <placetype />Center</placetype /></place /> on Global Climate Change, served on a morning panel that covered global climate change.</p><p>Humans are taking over as the major impact on the Earths climate, said Cohen, whose committee was established by House Speaker Nancy Pelosi. There are 6 billion of us on Earth, and we do a lot of things in our daily lives that create and emit greenhouse gases.</p><p>Roy</place /></city />, whose nonprofit organization works with business partners, recommended placing caps on the emissions of greenhouse gases and allowing companies to sell the rights to those emissions on the open market. </p><p>Its a way to allow government to determine what the environmental goal is and letting industry figure out how to get there, he said.</p><p>Jason Grummet, executive director of the National Commission on Energy Policy, said its unfortunate that fuel efficiency in automobiles has not increased in the lifetime of many of the high school students in the audience. Instead, advances in the industry have produced bigger and faster cars that consumers want, he said.</p><p>State Sen. Lee Constantine, R-Altamonte Springs, and state Rep. Bob Allen, <place /><placename />R-Merritt</placename /> <placetype />Island</placetype /></place />, described the importance of restoring the <place />Everglades</place />, preserving environmentally sensitive land and other state initiatives. </p><p>Canan, the UCF sociology professor, noted that climate change could lead to more environmental refugees as consequences such as more extreme droughts and floods develop. She also said diseases could spread to more areas as more climates become habitable for carriers such as mosquitoes.</p><p>So many people arent responsible for the environmental problems but will get to suffer the consequences, she said.</p><p>Wanielista, the director of UCFs <place /><placename />Stormwater</placename /> <placename />Management</placename /> <placetype />Academy</placetype /></place />, urged everyone in the audience to plant four trees. He also explored the environmental benefits of green roofs, which include keeping down temperatures and preserving storm-water. </p><p>The <place /><placename />Stormwater</placename /> <placename />Management</placename /> <placetype />Academy</placetype /></place /> monitors the green roof on the UCF Student Union expansion. Installed in spring 2005, the green roof coats half of the 3,200-square-foot expansion and is covered with plants such as dune sunflowers and bougainvillea. </p><p>The Lou Frey Institute of Politics and Government, which was founded in 2002 by former U.S. Rep. Lou Frey, is a nonpartisan foundation at UCF that engages in civic education for college and high school students and the public. The institute promotes informed discussion of issues from diverse viewpoints, encourages participation in the political process and supports research on politics and policy. </p><p>In addition to the Lou Frey Institute, sponsors of the symposium include Industrial Enterprises of America; Fifth Third Bank; Lowndes, Drosdick, Doster, Kantor and Reed; the UCF Global Perspectives Office; the UCF Political Science Department; the Orlando Sentinel; and the Global Connections Foundation. </p><p>For more information, go to <a href="http://www.loufrey.org/">www.loufrey.org</a>.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
		
			
		
	
